Here's What Will Happen When The Federal Reserve Raises The Interest Rate
The interest rate will rise and the bull market will stumble, bond yields will rise and the economy will go into recession.
That's what we know.
What we don’t know is how long it will happen and how long it will last.
In economics, history offers few clues as to the time frame.
After the first interest rate hike, the recession occurred in just 11 months and lasted 86 months.
The Federal Reserve’s aggressiveness to raise interest rates is often, though not always, a determining factor in how the economy and financial assets respond.
That is why U.S. central bank officials have emphasized so strongly that investors should not focus on when the interest rate starts to rise but on the trajectory of the time needed for normalization.
There are many variables at play.
But in the end, market players might find that all the fuss about raising the interest rate has been overblown.
“The Fed’s first rate hike since the global financial crisis will inevitably be interpreted by some as a sign of the ‘cheap money’ era,” Julian Jessop, chief economist at Capital Economics, said in a note to clients.
On the contrary, we do not expect the gradual return of US interest rates to more normal but still low levels to be the seismic shock that everyone seems to fear.
But it cannot be said that there will be no effects.
Below we present how some sectors of the economy could react, based on historical trends:
Given the situation that the market has faced in recent months, the anticipation of interest rate growth can volatilize things for a while.
But at the moment of growth, the impact is not so dramatic.
“There seems to be a trend for capital returns to stagnate for 12-24 months after the first increase, which may again reflect the monetary policy lapse,” Deutsche Bank analysts said in a recent study on what will happen after the Fed rises.
Specifically, in the last 35 years, the market has risen sharply - by about 14 percent - heading towards the interest rate increase, quite unchanged in the period of 250 days after (average rise of 2.6%) after which it returns to normal after 500 days, with an average recovery in the last six cycles of 14.4%, according to a recent analysis published on Barron’s Asvet by the strateul <0xC8><0x99>e<0xC8><0x99>en.
Deutsche said the impact on equities tends to become more pronounced later in the interest rate growth cycle and the benefits are starting to wane.
Recession is a reality of economic life, but rising interest rates often contribute to it.
In the current situation, the Fed is facing conditions that have not existed before and that could accelerate a recession.
Specifically, gross domestic product will approach its historical low for an increase in the Fed’s interest rate.
According to Deutsche Bank, of the 118 interest rate hikes since 1950, only twice nominal GDP was less than 4.5%.
Even though the value in the second quarter of 2015 was 3.6%, few expect the situation to persist, with the third quarter only reaching 1.5%, according to the Atlanta Fed.
Raising interest rates in such a fragile economy could be risky and could raise the question “if this time is different,” Deutsche said.
Market players have been gearing up all year for a Fed growth decision, with all eyes on this week’s meeting of the Federal Open Market Commission, which closes on Thursday.
Although many strategists and economists believe that the FOMC could approve an interest rate increase at this meeting, forward transactions indicate a probability of only 25%.
“In our post-1950 study, all interest rate growth cycles to date have been in a super cycle of profit growth, with GDP eclipsing pre-recession peaks very quickly after recovery began,” the report said.
On the contrary, this was a strangely slow recovery from the worst recession of the period under review.
The current cycle is by far the longest expected by the Fed since the end of the last recession; the record had been 35 months, and it reached 74 months and continues.
Fixed income was also volatile given that the market expects interest rate growth and the pattern is somewhat similar to that of dividends.
The main difference is that the impact is faster on bonds than on stocks when the Fed changes policy.
In the case of bonds, it seems that the benefits change direction as soon as the first increase/decrease in the cycle occurs.
At the end of the interest rate growth cycle, bond yields immediately fall," Deutsche said.
Charles Schwab’s strategies are of the opinion that these interest rate increases will bring short-term and long-term bonds closer to profitability by flattening the curve.
High-yield bonds do better in such an environment, although “we’re still cautious about forcing profitability,” Kathy Jones, a fixed-income analyst at Schwab, said in an analysis.
Interestingly, Jones believes that markets have already adapted to the Fed’s policy expectations.
“In addition to the strength of the dollar and lower estimated inflation, there are some signs that the market has adapted to the prospect of more rigorous monetary policy,” Jones wrote.
Short-term interest rates have risen, the yield curve is fairer, the average credit interest rate spread has expanded, and volatility has risen — all market characteristics when the Fed tightens policy.
Broadly speaking, companies operating mostly in the U.S. will benefit from rising interest rates and local products will become more attractive.
Multinationals with large debts will suffer because the growth of the dollar will lead to their products becoming more expensive in the global market space and their debt will be more expensive.
“History shows that ‘quality’ stocks tend to be more profitable in the three months following an initial interest rate increase,” Goldman Sachs said in a report to clients.
Firms with strong balance sheets outperformed those with weak balance sheets after each of the interest rate increases in 1994, 1999 and 2004, by an average of 5 percentage points.
Companies with large capital gains and low volatility stocks also outperformed similar companies with lower quality, with an average of 4 (percentage points) and 3 (percentage points) respectively.
Debt will become an important issue.
Companies with a high percentage of floating debt have the most to lose, Goldman says.
Consumers will also benefit from the dollar’s rise.
Those who save could also gain, although experts disagree about how quickly this will happen.
