Advantages and Disadvantages of Converting Credits to Swiss Francs
Two offers for the conversion of Swiss franc loans into lei have already appeared on the banking market, the main advantages being the exclusion of currency risk and the reduction of rates.
Disadvantages can come in a few years, when variable interest can lead to higher rates.
Banca Transilvania has just completed the process of converting loans into francs granted by Volksbank, and Bancpost has announced the conversion offer for its own clients.
According to the data compiled by analysts of the financial portal FinZoom, Bancpost offers three years of fixed interest on lei, 1.5%, the lowest on the market.
On the other hand, Banca Transilvania’s conversion offer was accepted by 83% of clients with franc loans due to two successive reductions: the balance was reduced with the amount of risk and administration fees paid by the client, then an additional reduction of 22.5% was applied to the balance in lei.
Both offers reduce the rates of their own customers, compared to the monthly payment equivalent in lei before conversion.
Thus, Banca Transilvania reduces the rate by 42.5% and Bancpost by 33% in the first three years and, theoretically, by 18% in the following years.
BENEFITS
The main advantage of CHF loans is that the currency risk is eliminated, the consumer is protected from future increases in the franc, and the credit will be repaid in the currency in which he collects his salary.
Another major advantage of both conversion offers is that there is no reassessment of the property, no additional guarantees and another proof of income.
Basically, there will not be a new financial and legal analysis of the credit, nor will there be additional costs as in the case of a refinancing.
Also, both banks offer a discount at the monthly rate, compared to how much customers pay before conversion, equivalent in lei.
Risks
The problem is that the rate in the first years is made up more of the interest, and the customer pays very little of the principal.
The Bancpost offer with very low interest rate in the first three years seems advantageous for customers.
However, it is not known how this rate will evolve after three years.
The margin offered to customers can be more than 3.25%, so on the whole, and the cost reduction is lower.
A possible risk for all loans in lei with variable interest rate is that the ROBOR index will grow significantly in the coming years (more than the Libor - CHF index).
For example, ROBOR at three months is now 1.44%, but in 2013 it had reached the value of 6%, in 2009, over 15%, and in a few days of 2008 it exceeded 40%!
In addition, other costs, not mentioned in the initial offer, may also arise.
