But some researchers have questioned the robustness of the data and pointed to links between some experts and the tobacco industry.
An article published last month in the medical journal Lancet attacked the “extraordinarily fragile basis” on which PHE founded its main conclusion.
Two other researchers writing in the BMJ questioned the claims and their substantiation “on solid earth or quicksand.”
Martin McKee, professor of European public health at the London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine, and Simon Capewell, professor of clinical epidemiology at the University of Liverpool, said: “A fundamental principle of public health is that policies must be based on evidence of effectiveness.”
They said they expected PHE’s claims that “current estimates show e-cigarettes are 95% less harmful than smoking” to be based on a detailed analysis of evidence and models.
In fact, a single meeting of 12 people led to the development of a multi-criteria decision analysis (MCDA) model to synthesize their views on the negative effects associated with different nicotine-containing products; the results of this meeting were briefly presented in a research paper.
McKee and Capewell said one of the sponsors of the meeting was a company called EuroSwiss Health, whose chief executive was said to have received funding in the past from British American Tobacco for conducting an independent study.
It also validated BAT’s public health accreditation in a sustainability report, he said.
They added that one of the 12 participants in the meeting stated the funding received from an e-cigarette manufacturer but not the funding that is reported to have been received from the cigarette and tobacco company, Philip Morris International.
The arguments on the basis of which the panel members were selected were not provided, but among them are a few "frontiers" known in the production of electronic cigarettes, some of whom even declare in the paper the financing of the industry.
Other participants in the meeting are not known for their expertise in tobacco control.
The meeting was also attended by the head of the tobacco control section of PHE.
The group’s research paper “mocks convincingly” that there is “a lack of solid evidence of the harmful effect that most products have by most criteria,” McKee and Capewell said.
However, none of these links or limitations are mentioned in the PHE report.
McKee and Capewell said PHE’s claims that “to date there is no evidence that e-cigarettes are a factor encouraging smoking among children or non-smokers” are premature.
Professor Kevin Fenton, director of PHE’s health department, says he has responded to BMJ’s claims in the past.
He said: “E-cigarettes are significantly less harmful than smoking.”
One in two people who have smoked for their entire lives lose their lives because of this addiction.
All the evidence suggests that the risk e-cigarettes pose to health is comparatively minor, but we need to continue to study the long-term effects.
PHE has a clear duty to inform the public about the information that emerges and the information that does not emerge from the evidence, in particular in view of the high degree of public confusion about the relative dangers compared to tobacco.
Every year, around 80,000 people lose their lives to a smoking-related disease and the annual costs to the national health system from smoking amount to <0xC2><0xA3>2 billion.
By clearly expressing the current evidence - namely that, although the use of e-cigarettes is not risk-free, they only present a fraction of the harmful effect of smoking - we are fulfilling our national duty.
