In Bach’s time there were no world tours.
Beethoven, Brahms, Bartok, Enescu were working people, who were artists and not commercial representatives.
For me, the organization of concerts, festivals, tours, the release of albums, all are formidable, extraordinary, but as long as they are done in the service of music.
If not, we are in a system where creativity suffers, it no longer has freedom.
To illustrate this phenomenon, David Grimal gave an example of Romanian products before and after joining the European Union: "In Romania, before entering the EU, you had good vegetables and meat".
To enter the EU, you had to pass health laws that are not good for vegetables and meat.
Production and agriculture end up in the service of supermarkets, as is also the case in France.
The same thing happens with music, it’s the same logic.
Les Dissonances makes tomatoes maybe not too beautiful, but when we cut them they are real tomatoes.
In an ideal world, this music should return to the center and the institutions and industries that manage this system understand that music does not need to be sold, but needs to be shared, and this can be done starting with educational policy.
“If we consider – as the Koreans, the Chinese, the Japanese do – that Western music is one of the most beautiful things of humanity, we would reintroduce its learning in school, we would reintroduce concerts on television and through this education we would no longer need to sell musical by-products,” Grimal believes.
Surely, there are things in classical music education that remain very communist, that everywhere, is something very militarized.
It depends on this discipline whether we compare a musician to a soldier, or whether we form a musician who will play an instrument, being, above all, a musician.
We’re talking about a completely different education, if we want to train a soldier, it has to be in a way, if we want to train a musician, it’s something else entirely.
In your opinion, which is more dangerous, a soldier or a musician?” asks the French artist smiling.
Grimal shows that, for artists, the reward of another way of making music comes precisely from the overcoming of this status of "soldier", the overcoming of what "they think are their limits": "Musicians discover at a certain moment that they are not soldiers, and therefore after the concert they come out smiling".
David Grimal spoke about his musical project and his vision of music and the artist in the "Festival of Ideas", a discussion with the public organized within the George Enescu International Festival by the Aspen Romania Institute.
