At the most anticipated meeting in years, policymakers at the Federal Reserve will spend two days this week around a 27-foot Honduran mahogany table to decide whether it’s time to raise a key interest rate for the first time in nearly a decade.
Above them, at one end of the meeting room of the central bank, a mural of the United States will be seen.
The map is meant to remind you that Janet L. Yellen, President of the Fed, and her colleagues must put the nation’s economic interests above all else.
The central bank has been given a dual task by Congress: to maximize the U.S. employment rate and maintain price stability.
But since the great economic crisis, Fed leaders have confirmed that there is a third unwritten task: financial stability.
And this third task could be the X factor in a decision too difficult to anticipate, which will be announced on Tuesday, and which will determine whether the U.S. economy is ready to be freed from the unprecedented incentive offered by the near-zero short-term interest rate in force since the end of 2008.
Even if most data point to a strong growing economy, recent turmoil in global financial markets could scare off already cautious Fed officials from adding volatility by raising the benchmark rate on federal funds — even by as little as a quarter of a percentage point.
“Obviously, the labor market and inflation will be the first and main issues that they will follow,” said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
“But I think that if they were looking for an excuse not to raise the interest rate, the growing uncertainty in the global market is enough to give them arguments to wait,” she said.
There is no consensus on the decision the Fed will take, which in itself causes instability in the financial market.
About half of the economists recently polled by Bloomberg anticipated a rise in the interest rate this week.
But financial markets expect the Fed to delay, a key indicator showing that the probability of growth is only 30%.
This would indicate a decline in the stock market if the Fed raises the interest rate, unless policymakers soften the blow by promising that it would be a long time before the next rise.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16,599.85.
The surge was triggered by expectations that Fed policymakers will keep interest rates steady this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
“It would be surprising if the Fed were to raise the interest rate right now,” Lonski said.
If Fed policymakers were to do so, “they should act in depth in their policies to avoid panic in financial markets.”
Other experts said a rise in the interest rate would calm financial markets because it would remove uncertainty about when the Fed will act.
Just a month ago, the Fed appeared to be on track to raise the rate by 0.25% this month, the first small step toward slowly tightening monetary conditions that would confirm the strength of the U.S. recovery.
Yellen said in spring and early summer that she expected an interest rate hike this year despite objections from liberals that more economic progress would be needed.
Although job creation slowed in August, labour market growth was solid this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1 percent last month, the lowest in more than seven years and close to the level the Fed considers total employment.
Earnings showed signs of growth.
And while inflation continued to fall short of the central bank’s annual target, Fed policymakers said a key reason was the temporary effect of sharply falling oil prices.
The economy "can cope with higher rates and needs them, given the strain on the labor market," said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But global financial markets began to go into a tailspin at the end of this month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones industrial average fell 16% below the record high reached in May as investors feared a slowdown in the Chinese economy would drag down global growth.
The market has somewhat rebounded this month, with the Dow now about 10% below its May high.
For Fed policymakers, market turmoil adds to the complex calculation of the timing of interest rate hikes.
“Without what’s happened in financial markets and news of China’s weakening economy in recent weeks, it would be firmer at the meeting,” said Stephen D. Oliner, a senior fellow at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former Fed official.
Now, he predicts that they will wait at least a month to better manage the effects.
“There is a lot of uncertainty about what the impact will be on the U.S. economy and they have almost no data to rely on after the events in China,” Oliner said.
The welfare of the global economy is not one of the Fed’s major interests, so it should practically not be taken into account in decision-making.
In reality, however, the Fed has become the world’s monetary authority.
In recent years, the influence of the central bank has been huge.
The mere allusion by then-President Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed could “narrow” its monetary expansion triggered an earthquake in global markets.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly twinned, Fed officials are expected not only to monitor progress elsewhere, but also to consult with other central banks and experts to better interpret the world economy.
His decision-making is “more art than science,” said Zachary Karabell, head of global strategy at welfare management firm Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, the president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, Va., said this month that “Fed has a history of overreacting to changes in the financial market that appear unrelated to economic fundamentals.”
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Commission, a decision-making body that supported the interest rate hike, gave the 1998-99 decisions as an example.
A financial crisis that hit Asia prompted the Fed to cut the benchmark rate by 0.75% in three meetings, "despite the limited identifiable implications for U.S. development," Lacker said.
A year later, Fed officials returned to those declines.
The Fed should put the issue of financial stability first only in the event of a major crisis, such as the 2008 market earthquake, said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England's interest rate committee.
The latest hectic period is nowhere near that level, he said.
“We certainly don’t want to be afraid of an interest rate hike because the markets are upset,” said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still has a double mandate and does not mention financial stability and, until something changes in this regard, I do not think it should take premature action.
