Four-fold increase in the number of children who have ingested hand detergent in the last 4 years
According to the Georgia Anti-Poison Center, anti-poison centers in the U.S. have reported an increase of about 400% since 2010 in the number of children under the age of 12 who swallowed high-alcohol hand detergent.
According to Dr. Gaylord Lopez, director of the Georgia Poison Control Center, cases of ingesting hand detergent in children under the age of 12 reported at poison control centers rose from 3,266 in 2010 to 16,117 in 2014.
“Children have more frequent access to these products, and unfortunately, a percentage of them end up in the emergency room,” Lopez told CNN.
Lopez said some kids intentionally drink detergent and others do it to impress their friends or respond to challenges on social media.
On YouTube you can watch movies that show teenagers how to drink detergent to create cheap drinks.
It turns out that teenagers mixed the mouthwash detergent with alcohol to get a stronger drink.
Younger children may be attracted to the attractive smell of detergent.
“A child doesn’t think it hurts him,” Lopez says.
Many of the most attractive types (hand detergents) are scented.
Hand detergents with strawberry, grape, orange flavor are the most attractive for children.
Hand detergent contains about 45-95% alcohol.
Especially in young children, just a few sips can cause alcohol poisoning.
“It’s very concentrated alcohol,” Dr. Stephen Thornton, medical director of the Kansas University Hospital’s poison control center, told the Kansas City Fox 4 channel.
Thus, we avoid leaving a glass of whiskey on the table, but people leave these hand detergents in accessible places and if the little ones get to them, this is a quick way to consume a lot of alcohol.
Nhaijah Russell, a six-year-old girl who recently ingested the equivalent of four sprays of strawberry-flavored hand detergent at school, has arrived at the emergency room for treatment.
Her blood alcohol level was 179, twice the threshold at which an adult is considered under the influence of alcohol by law, according to Dr. Chris Ritchey, an emergency room physician who treated her at Gwinnett Medical Center outside Atlanta.
Nhaijah was sulking and could not walk when he arrived at the emergency room.
Doctors monitored her overnight in a separate children’s hospital to identify signs of brain damage as the girl fell and hit her head because of alcohol, Ritchey said.
“It was scary,” Ortoria Scott, Nhaijah’s mother, told CNN.
It could have been fatal.
Lopez advised parents and teachers to use alcohol-free products or wipes and to keep hand detergent out of the reach of children.
In addition to alcohol poisoning, some detergents have been associated with deaths.
In 2013, two women in Ontario died after swallowing hand detergent containing an undeclared toxic ingredient.
The health authorities assumed that the product contained methanol, a lethal substance, and not ethyl alcohol, specified as an active ingredient.
In January, three fourth graders in upstate New York plotted to poison their “bad” teacher by “putting antibacterial products in the classroom,” according to a police report.
The teacher is very allergic to hand detergent and has banned it in her classroom.
The police considered the plan to be "insignificant" and referred the disciplinary issue to the school inspectorate.
