FriendsFest: the comedy series that taught us important lessons about friendship between men
The absence of similar characters in the series is evident, given that the need for men to open up is now more desperate than ever, with suicide rates among young men reaching a 15-year high.
In 2013, suicide was the leading cause of death in men aged 20-45 in the UK, and remains three times more common in men than in women.
In an attempt to address the issue, the Campaign Against Living Miserably (CALM) designated 2015 as the Year of the Man, seeking to challenge the culture that prevents men from asking for help when they need it.
Friendship is at the heart of the struggle to succeed in this challenge.
A recent study of more than 2,000 high school students who had symptoms of depression concluded that if the patient is surrounded by enough friends “with a healthy mood,” his chances of recovery double.
To the same extent, for people who are not depressed, a circle of mentally healthy friends halves the likelihood of mental disorders occurring.
Of course, for friendship to take effect, it must first be accessible.
In this age of communication dominated by social networks, where the emphasis is on style rather than substance, the immediate nature of the response often takes precedence over contact with meaning.
Our digital lives have doubled the need to create the appearance of a strong personality, open to fun and success, even if in reality it is isolation that dominates.
This superficial success is dominated by what psychologists call extrinsic values; money, image, social status, all at the cost of intrinsic values – our inner desire for personal development and friendship – that affect our mental health even more deeply.
The billionaire inventor of a video game recently explained that money doesn’t really buy happiness.
The beauty of Friends was that it focused attention on this idea.
The characters were not defined by their job but by their own personality, which they showed by interacting as friends.
The humor of Joey and Chandler’s frequent hugs, the moments when they look at football in the comfortable armchairs, and Ross’s passion for Rachel came from the fact that it is known that men can associate with this situation, even if they often shy away from fully exploring their feelings.
As one social worker explained to me: “My role in listening to suicidal and depressed people showed how even the smallest interactions with friends can make a difference.”
Often, people who turn to us do not feel able to talk to friends.
The old saying to do it yourself is strong, as is the feeling of being perceived as a weak person if you talk openly about problems.
Friends is one of the shows that comes to mind when I try to offer more psychological coping mechanisms in the long run.
The series highlighted the small moments of friendship between men.
No matter how much objective, outside intervention through the phone helps people in moments of desperation, long-term support comes from family and close friends.
So, if you’re attending this weekend’s FriendsFest hosted by Comedy Central, with full movie sets to celebrate the event, why not invite your friends over for a coffee in Central Perk.
Or, even better, if you see someone alone in Starbucks, smile and say hello.
You never know what difference your friendship will make.
