The mass layoff is the latest in a ten-year battle between the company and its more bloated flight attendants.
The weight limit for them dates back to the 1980s, when Air India started using charts with ideal weight and height.
In 2006, Air India fired nine female stewardesses who were considered "exceptionally overweight", as this "may have an effect on reflexes and impede the agility required to carry out emergency measures".
The stewardesses sued the company, won, and were rehired, but the company fired them again in 2009.
"All efforts to get them to lose weight have failed," a company spokesman said.
