Corbyn, Brexit and the future of Europe
For economic and demographic reasons, the prosperity they have enjoyed in the past decades cannot continue in the years to come.
By Saturday, few people in Romania knew who Jeremy Corbyn was.
Even today, after he has become the new leader of the UK Labour Party, many wonder to what extent the election of a politician who, after all, is not in a decision-making position can affect us.
Jeremy Corbyn is the most radical left-wing Labour leader since the war.
A declared Marxist, anti-monarchist (he once asked Tony Blair, then prime minister, to take the royal family out of Buckingham Palace), a fierce anti-American and a sympathizer of Vladimir Putin (he was also regularly invited to comment on political events in Britain and nuclear weapons by the "Russia Today" television channel), and on the terrorist movements of the United States.
For Corbyn, who at the time considered the killing of Osama bin Laden a real tragedy, ISIS is close to America’s favorite.
Following the model of all populist demagogues, Corbyn has, of course, miraculous anti-austerity solutions.
Things like what Tsipras was saying and promising in Greece until he came face to face with the real world and economic legacies.
The economic programme of the new Labour leader foresees, among other things, massive renationalisations and the printing of money as a solution to finance development projects and to cover very generous social benefits.
Of course, some may wonder why the solution with money printing is not unanimously adopted on the globe, we would then have a global general prosperity!, but who can prevent such details.
Of course, we can tax the bankers in blood, you become a kind of enemies of the service of the left, but from what has been seen so many times in the past, not only in the former communist states or in Ecuador or Venezuela, but also in France, at the beginning of the mandates of Mitterand and Hollande.
The extra amounts are quickly swallowed up by the generous, coverless promises made by populist demagogues.
As Margaret Thatcher said, “The problem with socialism is that at some point other people’s money runs out.”
Few give Jeremy Corbyn a real chance of ever becoming prime minister.
In the early 1980s another radical leftist leader, Michael Foot, who was not as extreme in his convictions as the party's new leader, failed miserably in the election.
And then there was still in Britain a working class, in the classical sense of the word, relatively consistent and structured.
And the unions were significantly more influential than they are now.
Under the new industrial landscape, where services are dominant in the workforce as a whole, and extensive automation has made the industry massively in need of a highly skilled workforce, Corbyn’s rhetoric has limited appeal.
But even in opposition, it can influence important developments that can affect us directly.
In its latest issue, the Financial Times believes that the election of Corbyn increases the chances of Brexit, respectively the exit of the United Kingdom from the EU.
The new Labour leader was a consistent opponent of the country's membership in the Union.
In the eyes of the radical left, Brussels is the agent of international capitalism and a promoter of globalization that has imposed austerity on the poor.
When you combine these kinds of ideas with those expressed by the radical right, with anti-immigration rhetoric, and you look at the refugee crisis that is shaking the foundations of the EU, you come up with an explosive mix.
And not just for the UK.
But if the British decide in the referendum, which is due to take place by 2017, to leave the Union the symbolic loss of capital for the entire European project and the deep fault lines created within it by the Euro crisis and now that of refugees, between North and South, between East and West, leaves room for the most worrying scenarios.
Especially since for a whole series of Member States, London was a counterweight to the Franco-German axis (in which Berlin becomes more and more the dominant actor anyway).
It is true that the British business environment, the City, are strong advocates of the country’s remaining in the EU.
But today’s Europe is no longer the Europe of the past.
There are many resentments, which are growing in intensity even in these weeks.
The problem is that Brussels, as I recently had a sample in Jean Clude Junker’s speech, tends more and more to make major decisions over the heads of the great majority of the Member States, consulting with only a few European powers, mainly with Germany.
And this is happening at a time when electoral support for anti-establishment, anti-immigration parties that are at the same time Eurosceptic is growing spectacularly across the continent.
In other words, the negative emotional climate has reached higher levels than ever before in the past.
Hence the conclusion that the Financial Times draws when assessing the chances of Brexit.
The pro-EU option is based on a cold calculation that departs from the national interest.
If voters make the brain decision, then Britain will remain in the EU.
But Corbyn’s victory reminds us of the power of emotion in current politics.
However, Eastern Europe can be significantly affected by such major developments.
Especially if, as expected, we witness a more pronounced integration of the Eurozone, which will push most of the states in the region to the periphery of interest and decision-making in Europe.
Corbyn, Tsipras and Syriza in Greece, Podemos in Spain, even Bernie Sanders in the United States fuel their populist rhetoric from the frustrations accumulated in Western societies.
For economic and demographic reasons, the prosperity enjoyed in the last decades, the generous social benefits, cannot continue the same in the following years.
Under the explosive pressure of the dual crisis, the Eurozone - immigration, both caused by hasty decisions that took into account only integrationist political ambitions, not the ability and willingness of the peoples and governments of Europe to respond to such challenges, the turbulence on the continent, the internal tensions in the EU will increase in intensity and can greatly affect the situation of Romania.
And it’s hard to rule out anything from the point of view of possible scenarios.
The question is whether our main political leaders are able to cope with such complicated situations.
